From: Anthony Iliopoulos <ailiop@suse.com>
Date: Fri, 20 Mar 2026 16:34:57 +0100
Subject: fs: skip superblock shrink on frozen xfs filesystems
Patch-mainline: Never, SUSE-specific, upstream has async inode freeing
References: bsc#1259770

Ensure that the fs is not frozen before proceeding with inode eviction
since calling into filesystem code may require writing.

This is especially the case for xfs, since during destroy_inode the
inactivation code will possibly need to free any preallocated post-eof
blocks, and that can block on transaction allocation waiting to acquire
the sb_writers rwsem in sb_start_intwrite.

All this is called synchronously from the same calling context (e.g.
kswapd on background reclaim), and can cause a deadlock on an already
frozen filesystem since thaw_super requires acquisition of the s_umount
superblock lock which is already taken during super_cache_scan.

This is more properly addressed upstream by implementing asynchronous
inode deactivation running from a workqueue context.

Fix this by just skipping shrinking on xfs filesystems that are in a
frozen state.

Signed-off-by: Anthony Iliopoulos <ailiop@suse.com>
---
 fs/super.c | 6 ++++++
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+)

diff --git a/fs/super.c b/fs/super.c
index ea38a599999d..1120340a548c 100644
--- a/fs/super.c
+++ b/fs/super.c
@@ -75,6 +75,12 @@ static unsigned long super_cache_scan(struct shrinker *shrink,
 	if (!trylock_super(sb))
 		return SHRINK_STOP;
 
+	if (sb->s_writers.frozen != SB_UNFROZEN &&
+			sb->s_magic == 0x58465342 /* XFS_SB_MAGIC */) {
+		up_read(&sb->s_umount);
+		return SHRINK_STOP;
+	}
+
 	if (sb->s_op->nr_cached_objects)
 		fs_objects = sb->s_op->nr_cached_objects(sb, sc);
 

